'''Yegor Nikolaevich Solyankin''' ({{Lang-ru|Егор Николаевич Солянкин}}; 1901{{En dash}}26 June 1941) was a [[Red Army]] [[major general]]. Solyankin led the [[2nd Tank Division (Soviet Union)|2nd Tank Division]] during the [[Battle of Raseiniai]], a Soviet counterattack after the [[German invasion of the Soviet Union]]. He was killed in action during the defeat of his division.
== Early life == Solyankin was born on 21 April 1901<ref>Irretrievable loss report, available online at [http://www.obd-memorial.ru/html/info.htm?id=3220031 obd-memorial.ru]</ref> in [[Moscow]]. He was orphaned at age four and was sent to be raised in a peasant family in a village in [[Gzhatsky Uyezd]]. Solyankin was a shepherd in the village. From the age of twelve he worked as a blacksmith in Moscow.<ref name=":0">{{Cite news|url=http://www.ohotniki.ru/hunting/article/2015/05/19/643887-dve-lyubvi-zabyitogo-generala.html|title=Две любви забытого генерала|last=Dobrovolsky|first=Alexander|date=19 May 2015|work=Ohotniki|language=Russian|trans-title=Forgotten General had two loves|access-date=11 October 2016|via=}}</ref> In June 1920, he was drafted into the [[Red Army]].<ref name=":1">{{Cite web|url=http://www.pobeda1945.su/frontovik/33421|title=Солянкин Егор Николаевич|last=|first=|date=|website=www.pobeda1945.su|publisher=|language=Russian|trans-title=Solyankin Yegor Nikolaevich|access-date=2016-10-11}}</ref>
== Military career == Solyankin, originally an infantryman, transferred to armor in 1932. In 1936, he served as commander of a tank battalion of the [[1st Rifle Division (Soviet Union)|1st Rifle Division]] at [[Kazan]]. From July 1938, he commanded the [[2nd Tank Brigade (Soviet Union)|2nd Tank Brigade]] in the [[Leningrad Military District]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mechcorps.rkka.ru/files/before_41/pages/02_tp_tbr.htm|title=2 танковый полк 2 танковая бригада|last=Drig|first=Yevgeny|date=4 April 2009|website=mechcorps.rkka.ru|publisher=|language=Russian|trans-title=2nd Tank Regiment 2nd Tank Brigade|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121019145431/http://mechcorps.rkka.ru/files/before_41/pages/02_tp_tbr.htm|archive-date=19 October 2012|access-date=11 October 2016}}</ref> Solyankin became commander of the [[18th Light Tank Brigade (Soviet Union)|18th Light Tank Brigade]] in 1939, when it was stationed in Estonia at [[Uuemõisa (borough)|Uuemõisa]] as a result of the [[Soviet–Estonian Mutual Assistance Treaty]],{{sfn|Hiio, ed.|2006|p=17}} and participated in the [[Soviet annexation of Estonia]] in June 1940. During the annexation, the brigade advanced into [[Tallinn]]. On 4 June 1940, he was promoted to [[Major General]].<ref>[http://www.rkka.ru/handbook/personal/945.htm Resolution No. 945 of the Council of the People's Commissars of the USSR]</ref> He then served as deputy commander of the [[1st Mechanized Corps (Soviet Union)|1st Mechanized Corps]]. Solyankin became commander of the [[2nd Tank Division (Soviet Union)|2nd Tank Division]], part of the [[3rd Mechanised Corps (Soviet Union)|3rd Mechanized Corps]], on 9 December.<ref name=":1" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mechcorps.rkka.ru/files/mechcorps/pages/biograf_s.htm|title=Биографии - С|last=Drig|first=Yevgeny|date=30 December 2007|website=mechcorps.rkka.ru|publisher=|language=Russian|trans-title=Biographies - S|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121010095723/http://mechcorps.rkka.ru/files/spravochnik/personalii/biograf_s.htm|archive-date=10 October 2012|access-date=11 October 2016}}</ref> In the early summer of 1941 he arranged for the evacuation of the families of officers, although this was not officially permitted.<ref name=":0" />
=== World War II === During the [[Operation Barbarossa|invasion of Russia]], the 3rd Mechanized Corps mounted a counterattack against the advancing [[XXXXI Panzer Corps]] in what become known as the [[Battle of Raseiniai]]. The 2nd Tank Division had marched a hundred kilometers from [[Kėdainiai]] on 23 June to make its planned assault the following day. The division had six different types of tanks, including 32 [[Kliment Voroshilov tank|KV-1]]<nowiki/>s, 19 KV-2s, and 50 [[T-34]]<nowiki/>s. Nearly half of the KVs broke down during the march. The KV tank<nowiki/>s and T-34<nowiki/>s of the division surprised the troops of the [[6th Panzer Division (Wehrmacht)|6th Panzer Division]], who were unaware of the existence of the Soviet tanks. The attack caused temporary panic, but the German forces counterattacked when the 2nd Tank Division ran out of fuel and ammunition after making six attacks. The [[1st Panzer Division (Wehrmacht)|1st Panzer Division]] and the [[36th Infantry Division (Wehrmacht)|36th Infantry Division]] flanked Solyankin's division and its rear area was captured after the [[8th Panzer Division (Wehrmacht)|8th Panzer Division]] took Kėdainiai. On 25 June, Solyankin led a breakout attempt with the remaining heavy tanks leading. The division was destroyed and Solyankin was killed on 26 June.{{Sfn|Maslov|1998|p=5}}{{Sfn|Forczyk|2014|pp=40{{endash}}41}} The location of his burial is unknown.<ref name=":0" /> He was survived by his wife, Varvara Vasilievna, a daughter, Raisa, and a son, Alexander.<ref name=":1" />
